\pard\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\sl264\slmult1\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \'93Half of her friends are already linked,\'94 says Peter, switching back to voice. \'93Before the year is out, the other half will be too.\'94 Peter leans forward, resting his elbows on his knees. \'93She\'92s a smart kid. You\'92ve been preparing her for this. We both have.\'94\
\
\'93That\'92s not the point.\'94 Jill sets her cup down with a sharp clink. \'93It\'92s not about how smart she is or mature she is \'97 it\'92s about what this technology can do to people. The phone is bad enough: Real-time data streams, immersive experiences, intelligent agents.\'94\
\
\'93Jill, we can track her usage, set limits, teach her digital responsibility. \'97 We\'92re doing that now with how she uses her tablet.\'94\
\
\'93But the neural link? It\'92s a whole different world. Everything, everyone, only a thought away. It\'92s too much, Peter. Too much connectivity, too soon.\'94\
\
Peter gives her a small, reassuring smile. \'93The link is only an interface to her phone. Her usage shows up in the app, like anything else. They block the link and cell phone usage at school, and we could add off-link time to our off-screen time.\'94\
\
Jill pulls back her dark hair, looking unconvinced.\
\
\'93You work with connectivity every day,\'94 Peter reminds her. \'93You trust it to keep our nation secure. Why not trust it for our child?\'94\
\
Jill turns to face him, crossing her arms. \'93Because I know exactly how powerful it is to have access to everything. I see the good it can do, sure, but I also see the dangers \'97 data breaches, manipulation, over-reliance. A twelve-year-old brain is still developing. The ability to separate reality from synthetic reality is \'85 fragile. What if she gets overwhelmed? What if something goes wrong? A malfunction, a hack, a \'97\'94\
\
\'93Gillian \'85\'94 Peter interrupts, his voice quiet. He stands up, taking her hands in his. \'93You and I have had neural links since college. Kids start younger now. Some parentals are chipping six-year-olds with GPS. \'97 If you\'92re concerned about the implant, we could start Julie on a BCI headset.\'94\
\
Jill uncrosses her arms. \'93No, we don\'92t have to go that far. I know it\'92s a simple outpatient procedure, covered by National Health. We can have the nurse practitioner handle it at the doctor\'92s office.\'94\
\
Peter continues. \'93You\'92ve given lectures on how to integrate SI into people\'92s lives the right way. You\'92ve written protocols for ethical SI use. You\'92ve spent years making sure our technology is safe. You can guide her through it. You will guide her through it.\'94\
\
Jill sighs, the tension in her shoulders easing under his calming touch. \'93I know. I just \'85 I feel like once we give her that neural link, we\'92re opening a door we can\'92t close. She\'92ll be more connected to the world than we ever were at her age. And what if we lose her to this \'85 this \'85 endless digital noise?\'94\
\
Peter tilts his head, his gaze warm and steady. \'93Or what if she thrives? What if this step gives her opportunities we never had? She could learn faster, experience more, find her passions earlier. You always say the future is about balance. We can help her find the right balance.\'94\
\
Jill closes her eyes for a moment. When she opens them again, she sees her own concern reflected in her spouse\'92s face \'97 but also his hope. She nods and links:\
\
\'93
\f1\i Okay. But we set boundaries. Strict ones. Same as the tablet. No unrestricted access. We\'92ll take it slow. Monitor everything.
\f0\i0 \'94\
\
Peter smiles, kisses her forehead, and links, \'93
\f1\i We\'92ll do it together.
\f0\i0 \'94\
\
Jill leans back and smiles weakly in return and says out loud, \'93Together.\'94 \
\
She glances over at the family portrait on the wall. Her gaze lingers on their oldest offspring\'92s bright, curious eyes. Her heart still feels heavy, but beneath the weight, there was a glimmer of cautious optimism.\
\
Behind her, the house bot quietly collects her forgotten cup of tea.\
\
