{\*\bkmkstart Dish_}The{\*\bkmkend Dish_} Ryugyong Elite Social Club is a quiet sanctuary for the elite wives of Ch\'e1oxi\uc0\u462 n\'92s upper echelons.\
\
Polished wood panels and delicate porcelain vases adorn the private dining room. The faint hum of traditional Ch\'e1oxi\uc0\u462 n music plays in the background. Kim Soo-jin, the wife of General Ri Sun-hyuk, adjusts the placement of her napkin. Across from her sits Han Mi-young. She is the wife of Choi Hyun-seok, the vice minister of the Reconnaissance General Bureau.\
\
A server pours steaming tea into delicate cups, then bows and retreats. The two women exchange polite smiles. An undercurrent of tension flows beneath an ocean of cordiality.\
\
Kim Soo-jin (Ri\'92s wife) greets her lunch companion. \'93I\'92m so glad we could find time to meet, Mi-young. It feels like our husbands are always so busy these days. Do they even remember what our dining rooms look like?\'94\
\
Soo-jin\'92s voice carries a light laugh. But her eyes reveal the exhaustion of a woman accustomed to living in the shadow of duty.\
\
Han Mi-young (Choi\'92s wife) takes a sip of her tea, nodding with sympathy. \'93You\'92re not alone in that. Hyun-seok is either buried in reports or in some closed-door meeting. He says he\'92s working to protect the nation, but I can\'92t help wondering if he ever thinks about protecting his own health.\'94\
\
Her tone is soft. But there\'92s a flicker of resentment as she sets down her cup.\
\
\'93Sun-hyuk is the same. He says the same things \'97 about the nation, the duty, the honor. And I understand, of course. But \'85 it\'92s lonely, isn\'92t it? They\'92re there. But not there. Always thinking about the next crisis or enemy.\'94\
\
She glances out the window. A cherry blossom tree sways in the wind. Her expression is wistful.\
\
Mi-young offers a knowing smile. \'93It is. They forget that we also bear the weight of their responsibilities in our own way. Lately, I\'92ve had to field so many prying questions about his work. People seem to think I have all the answers.\'94\
\
Her voice lowers before continuing. \'93Of course, I don\'92t. He tells me very little. I know it is for my safety. But it doesn\'92t make it any easier, does it?\'94\
\
\'93No, it doesn\'92t,\'94 Soo-jin replies, her voice soft. \'93Sun-hyuk rarely speaks about work either. When he does, it\'92s always the same tone: cold, measured. Like he\'92s rehearsing what he can say, even to me.\'94\
\
Mi-young hesitates. Then she adds, \'93I don't know if he\'92s even capable of relaxing anymore. When he\'92s home, Hyun-seok hardly speaks. It\'92s like the war room follows him into our house.\'94\
\
Mi-young sighs, resting her chin on her hand. \'93Hyun-seok is different in that way. He talks more, but it\'92s \'85 selective. He\'92ll share frustrations about incompetence, or joke about something mundane. But never about what matters. I don\'92t know if it\'92s because he doesn\'92t trust me or if he\'92s trying to shield me.\'94\
\
She pauses, then Mi-young leans forward. \'93Do you ever think about what life would have been like if they weren\'92t so devoted to their careers?\'94\
\
Soo-jin\'92s lips curve into a faint smile. A smile tinged with sadness. \'93Sometimes I think of him teaching at the military academy, spending more time at home. Even taking up gardening, like he used to talk about when we were younger. But then I remind myself \'97 he wouldn\'92t be Sun-hyuk if he wasn\'92t this person. Duty is who he is.\'94\
\
She looks at Mi-young, her expression softening. \'93What about you? Did you ever wish for something simpler?\'94\
\
Mi-young chuckles. \'93Oh, all the time. Before we married, Hyun-seok used to dream about opening a bookstore. Can you imagine? A bookstore, here, in the capital city?\'94\
\
The thought draws laughter from both women. \
\
\'93But as you said, that\'92s not who they are. And that\'92s why we married them. Their ambition, their loyalty. It\'92s what draws people to them. It\'92s what makes them who they are.\'94\
\
Soo-jin nods. \'93It\'92s true. And yet \'97 do they realize what it costs us? We keep their homes, their families, their reputations intact. So they fight their battles. But who takes care of us?\'94\
\
Her voice softens, almost to a whisper. \'93We\'92re strong, but even the strongest need someone to lean on.\'94\
\
Mi-young reaches across the table. She places a hand over Soo-jin\'92s. \'93Then we can lean on each other. If we\'92re going to be in their shadows, let\'92s make sure that we don\'92t disappear. We\'92re stronger together, don\'92t you think?\'94\
\
For the first time that day, Soo-jin smile is warm. Gratitude glows in her eyes. \'93You\'92re right. Thank you, Mi-young.\'94\
\
The two women sit in silence for a moment, sharing the camaraderie. They sip hot tea. The cherry blossoms outside sway in the breeze. \
\
It is a rare moment of peace in a life filled with duty.\
