\cf0 \'93{\*\bkmkstart Cover_Up}Thank{\*\bkmkend Cover_Up} you for coming so quickly,\'94 says a woman sitting down behind a modest metal desk.\
\
\'93You\'92re welcome, Mrs. Baxter. Your report said that a body has been abducted?\'94\
\
Two people in business attire sit across from the hospital administrator\'92s desk. One is the hospital\'92s attorney. The other is a California Bureau of Investigation agent. The attorney is better dressed.\
\
\'93The body disappeared. It must have been taken,\'94 says the attorney.\
\
The hospital administrator cuts in. \'93We searched the morgue and confirmed that every other body is in its assigned drawer, and every other drawer is empty. We checked the footage for the room and for the hallway. Everything looks normal, except for the brief power outage.\'94\
\
\'93Power outage?\'94 asks the agent.\
\
\'93Yes,\'94 says the attorney, \'93At 17:03, there was a power fluctuation. We lost the lights and cameras for 25 seconds until the secondary generator came online.\'94\
\
\'93There\'92s no way someone got in and out with a body in that time,\'94 says the administrator.\
\
\'93Did you try?\'94 asks the investigator.\
\
\'93Even if someone made it into the morgue and back to the hall,\'93 explains the administrator, \'93it would take at least a minute to carry the body up the stairs. And the elevator was shut down during the blackout.\'94\
\
\'93OK,\'94 said the investigator, pulling out his phone. \'93I\'92m making a secure call back to headquarters to close your report as a false alarm. We don\'92t need the media raising fears about missing bodies. I\'92ll file another report when we resolve the matter.\'94\
\
The attorney and administrator blink and turn their heads to look at each other, but say nothing.\
\
\'93What are the hospital\'92s next steps now, special agent?\'94 asks the attorney.\
\
The agent pauses, steepling his fingers and leaning back into the chair.\
\
\'93Is the family waiting for the body? \'97 It\'92s not a celebrity or anything like that?\'94\
\
\'93The body belonged to Brent Geller,\'94 explained the administrator. \'93The deceased was in that car accident on El Camino Real. It was all over the media. The family agreed to donate his organs. We would usually deliver the cremains sometime tomorrow.\'94\
\
\'93Let me reach out to our body farm. We cremate several bodies a week as the experiments run their course. I\'92ll get us some replacement ashes.\'94\
\
\'93You want to give the family someone else\'92s ashes?\'94 asked the administrator.\
\
\'93At this point, they either get nothing or ashes from the farm. When we find the body, we can exchange the ashes. Would you rather tell them you lost the body or mixed-up the ashes?\'94\
\
The attorney and administrator look at each other, slack jawed, eyes wide.\
\
\'93It\'92s the memories that count,\'94 says the special agent.\
\
\
